# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: waf-rule-tuning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] An **application firewall** is a form of firewall that controls input/output or system calls of an application or service.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] It operates by monitoring and blocking communications based on a configured policy, generally with predefined rule sets to choose from.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] The two primary categories of application firewalls are *network-based* and *host-based*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Gene Spafford of Purdue University, Bill Cheswick at AT&T Laboratories, and Marcus Ranum described a third-generation firewall known as an application layer firewall.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Marcus Ranum's work, based on the firewall created by Paul Vixie, Brian Reid, and Jeff Mogul, spearheaded the creation of the first commercial product.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] The product was released by DEC, named the DEC SEAL by Geoff Mulligan - Secure External Access Link.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] DEC's first major sale was on June 13, 1991, to Dupont.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Under a broader DARPA contract at TIS, Marcus Ranum, Wei Xu, and Peter Churchyard developed the Firewall Toolkit (FWTK) and made it freely available under license in October 1993.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] However, FWTK was a basic application proxy requiring the user interactions.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] In 1994, Wei Xu extended the FWTK with the Kernel enhancement of IP stateful filter and socket transparent.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] This was the first transparent firewall, known as the inception of the third generation firewall, beyond a traditional application proxy (the second generation firewall), released as the commercial product known as Gauntlet firewall.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Gauntlet firewall was rated one of the top application firewalls from 1995 until 1998, the year it was acquired by Network Associates Inc, (NAI).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Network Associates continued to claim that Gauntlet was the "worlds most secure firewall" but in May 2000, security researcher Jim Stickley discovered a large vulnerability in the firewall, allowing remote access to the operating system and bypassing the security controls.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Stickley discovered a second vulnerability a year later, effectively ending Gauntlet firewalls' security dominance.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Application layer filtering operates at a higher level than traditional security appliances.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] This allows packet decisions to be made based on more than just source/destination IP Address or ports and can also use information spanning across multiple connections for any given host.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Network-based application firewalls operate at the application layer of a TCP/IP stack and can understand certain applications and protocols such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Domain Name System (DNS), or Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] This allows it to identify unwanted applications or services using a non standard port or detect if an allowed protocol is being abused.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Web application firewalls (WAF) are a specialized version of a network-based appliance that acts as a reverse proxy, inspecting traffic before being forwarded to an associated server.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] A host-based application firewall monitors application system calls or other general system communication.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] This gives more granularity and control, but is limited to only protecting the host it is running on.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Control is applied by filtering on a per process basis.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Generally, prompts are used to define rules for processes that have not yet received a connection.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Further filtering can be done by examining the process ID of the owner of the data packets.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Many host-based application firewalls are combined or used in conjunction with a packet filter.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Due to technological limitations, modern solutions such as sandboxing are being used as a replacement of host-based application firewalls to protect system processes.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Application firewalls are available in various forms, including free and open-source software as well as commercial products.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Starting with Mac OS X Leopard, an implementation of the TrustedBSD MAC framework (taken from FreeBSD), was included.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] The TrustedBSD MAC framework is used to sandbox services and provides a firewall layer, given the configuration of the sharing services in Mac OS X Leopard and Snow Leopard.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] Third-party applications can provide extended functionality, including filtering out outgoing connections by app.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/application-firewall] These devices may be sold as hardware, software, or virtualized network appliances.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] The platform provides a rule configuration language known as 'SecRules' for real-time monitoring, logging, and filtering of Hypertext Transfer Protocol communications based on user-defined rules.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Although not its only configuration, ModSecurity is most commonly deployed to provide protections against generic classes of vulnerabilities using the OWASP ModSecurity Core Rule Set (CRS).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] This is an open-source set of rules written in ModSecurity's SecRules language.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] The project is part of OWASP, the Open Web Application Security Project.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Several other rule sets are also available.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] To detect threats, the ModSecurity engine is deployed embedded within the webserver or as a proxy server in front of a web application.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] This allows the engine to scan incoming and outgoing HTTP communications to the endpoint.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Dependent on the rule configuration the engine will decide how communications should be handled which includes the capability to pass, drop, redirect, return a given status code, execute a script, and more.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] ModSecurity was first developed by Ivan Ristić, who wrote the module with the end goal of monitoring application traffic on the Apache HTTP Server.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] The first version was released in November 2002 which supported Apache HTTP Server 1.3.x.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Starting in 2004 Ivan created Thinking Stone to continue work on the project full-time.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] While working on the version 2.0 rewrite Thinking Stone was bought by Breach Security, an American-Israeli security company, in September 2006.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Ivan stayed on continuing the development of version 2.0 which was subsequently released in October 2006 at the OWASP AppSec conference in Seattle.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Ristić and Breach Security released another major rewrite, version 2.5, with major syntactic changes in February 2008.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] In December 2008 Ivan left Breach to found SSL Labs.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Shortly after Ivan's departure from Breach Security, Trustwave Holdings acquired Breach in June 2010 and relicensed ModSecurity under the Apache license.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Development continued and the new license allowed easier integration of ModSecurity into other products.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] As a result of this there was steady adoption of ModSecurity by various commercial products.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] The license change also precipitated easier porting of the software.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Hence, Microsoft contributed an IIS port in August 2012 and the port for Nginx was released at Black Hat Briefings in 2012.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] 2017 saw the second edition of the handbook released, written by Christian Folini and Ivan Ristić.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] It covers ModSecurity up to version 2.9.2.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] Being originally an Apache module, porting ModSecurity to other platforms was time-consuming and had high maintenance costs.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] As a result of this, a complete rewrite was started in December 2015.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] This new iteration, libmodsecurity, changes the underlying architecture, separating ModSecurity into a standalone engine that communicates with the web server via an API.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] This modular architecture-based WAF, which was announced for public use in January 2018, became libmodsecurity (ModSecurity version 3.0) and has supported connectors for Nginx and Apache.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] In 2021, Trustwave Holdings, announce the End-of-Sale (EOS) of Trustwave support for ModSecurity effective August 1, 2021 and the End-of-Life (EOL) of support effective July 1, 2024.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/modsecurity] The maintenance of the ModSecurity code is given to the open-source community.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/owasp] Mark Curphey started OWASP on September 9, 2001.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/owasp] Jeff Williams served as the volunteer Chair of OWASP from late 2003 until September 2011.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/owasp] As of 2015, Matt Konda chaired the Board.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/owasp] The OWASP Foundation, a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization in the US established in 2004, supports the OWASP infrastructure and projects.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/owasp] Since 2011, OWASP is also registered as a non-profit organization in Belgium under the name of OWASP Europe VZW.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/owasp] In February 2023, it was reported by Bil Corry, a OWASP Foundation Global Board of Directors officer, on Twitter that the board had voted for renaming from the Open Web Application Security Project to its current name, replacing Web with Worldwide.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/owasp] In May 2023, the OWASP Gen AI Security Project was started to expand the scope of the OWASP Top 10 List to document the most critical risks associated with LLMs.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/owasp] These certifications help professionals demonstrate expertise in secure development, testing, and application security management across different organizational roles and technical disciplines.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A **regular expression** (shortened as **regex** or **regexp**), sometimes referred to as a **rational expression**, is a sequence of characters that specifies a match pattern in text.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Usually such patterns are used by string-searching algorithms for "find" or "find and replace" operations on strings, or for input validation.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regular expression techniques are developed in theoretical computer science and formal language theory.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The concept of regular expressions began in the 1950s, when the American mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene formalized the concept of a regular language.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] They came into common use with Unix text-processing utilities.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Different syntaxes for writing regular expressions have existed since the 1980s, one being the POSIX standard and another, widely used, being the Perl syntax.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are used in search engines, in search and replace dialogs of word processors and text editors, in text processing utilities such as sed and AWK, and in lexical analysis.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are supported in many programming languages.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Library implementations are often called an "engine", and many of these are available for reuse.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions originated in 1951, when mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene described regular languages using his mathematical notation called *regular events*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] These arose in theoretical computer science, in the subfields of automata theory (models of computation) and the description and classification of formal languages, motivated by Kleene's attempt to describe early artificial neural networks.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions entered popular use from 1968 in two uses: pattern matching in a text editor and lexical analysis in a compiler.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Among the first appearances of regular expressions in program form was when Ken Thompson built Kleene's notation into the editor QED as a means to match patterns in text files.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by just-in-time compilation (JIT) to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System, an important early example of JIT compilation.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Around the same time that Thompson developed QED, a group of researchers including Douglas T.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Ross implemented a tool based on regular expressions that is used for lexical analysis in compiler design.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Many variations of these original forms of regular expressions were used in Unix programs at Bell Labs in the 1970s, including lex, sed, AWK, and expr, and in other programs such as vi, and Emacs (which has its own, incompatible syntax and behavior).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regexes were subsequently adopted by a wide range of programs, with these early forms standardized in the POSIX.2 standard in 1992.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In the 1980s, the more complicated regexes arose in Perl, which originally derived from a regex library written by Henry Spencer (1986), who later wrote an implementation for Tcl called *Advanced Regular Expressions*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The Tcl library is a hybrid NFA/DFA implementation with improved performance characteristics.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Software projects that have adopted Spencer's Tcl regular expression implementation include PostgreSQL.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Perl later expanded on Spencer's original library to add many new features.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Part of the effort in the design of Raku (formerly named Perl 6) is to improve Perl's regex integration, and to increase their scope and capabilities to allow the definition of parsing expression grammars.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The result is a mini-language called Raku rules, which are used to define Raku grammar as well as provide a tool to programmers in the language.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] These rules maintain existing features of Perl 5.x regexes, but also allow BNF-style definition of a recursive descent parser via sub-rules.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The use of regexes in structured information standards for document and database modeling started in the 1960s and expanded in the 1980s when industry standards like ISO SGML (precursored by ANSI "GCA 101-1983") consolidated.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The kernel of the structure specification language standards consists of regexes.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Its use is evident in the DTD element group syntax.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Prior to the use of regular expressions, many search languages allowed simple wildcards, for example "*" to match any sequence of characters, and "?" to match a single character.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Relics of this can be found today in the glob syntax for filenames, and in the SQL `LIKE` operator.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Starting in 1997, Philip Hazel developed PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expressions), which attempts to closely mimic Perl's regex functionality and is used by many modern tools including PHP and Apache HTTP Server.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Today, regexes are widely supported in programming languages, text processing programs (particularly lexers), advanced text editors, and some other programs.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regex support is part of the standard library of many programming languages, including Java and Python, and is built into the syntax of others, including Perl and ECMAScript.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The phrase *regular expressions*, or *regexes*, is often used to mean the specific, standard textual syntax for representing patterns for matching text, as distinct from the mathematical notation described below.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Each character in a regular expression (that is, each character in the string describing its pattern) is either a metacharacter, having a special meaning, or a regular character that has a literal meaning.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, in the regex `b.`, 'b' is a literal character that matches just 'b', while '.' is a metacharacter that matches every character except a newline.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Therefore, this regex matches, for example, 'b%', or 'bx', or 'b5'.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Together, metacharacters and literal characters can be used to identify text of a given pattern or process a number of instances of it.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Pattern matches may vary from a precise equality to a very general similarity, as controlled by the metacharacters.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, `.` is a very general pattern, `[a-z]` (match all lowercase letters from 'a' to 'z') is less general and `b` is a precise pattern (matches just 'b').
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The metacharacter syntax is designed specifically to represent prescribed targets in a concise and flexible way to direct the automation of text processing of a variety of input data, in a form easy to type using a standard ASCII keyboard.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A very simple case of a regular expression in this syntax is to locate a word spelled two different ways in a text editor; for example, the regular expression `seriali[sz]e` matches both "serialise" and "serialize".
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Wildcard characters also achieve this, but are more limited in what they can pattern, as they have fewer metacharacters and a simple language-base.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The usual context of wildcard characters is in globbing similar names in a list of files, whereas regexes are usually employed in applications that pattern-match text strings in general.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, the regex `^[ \t]+|[ \t]+$` matches excess whitespace at the beginning or end of a line.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A **regex processor** translates a regular expression in the above syntax into an internal representation that can be executed and matched against a string representing the text being searched in.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] One possible approach is the Thompson's construction algorithm to construct a nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA), which is then made deterministic and the resulting deterministic finite automaton (DFA) is run on the target text string to recognize substrings that match the regular expression.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The picture shows the NFA scheme `*N*(*s**)` obtained from the regular expression `*s**`, where *s* denotes a simpler regular expression in turn, which has already been recursively translated to the NFA *N*(*s*).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A regular expression, often called a *pattern*, specifies a set of strings required for a particular purpose.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A simple way to specify a finite set of strings is to list its elements or members.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] However, there are often more concise ways: for example, the set containing the three strings "Handel", "Händel", and "Haendel" can be specified by the pattern `H(ä|ae?)ndel`; we say that this pattern *matches* each of the three strings.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] However, there can be many ways to write a regular expression for the same set of strings: for example, `(Hän|Han|Haen)del` also specifies the same set of three strings in this example.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Most formalisms provide the following operations to construct regular expressions.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] are equivalent patterns which both describe the set of "gray" or "grey".
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] , character, or group) specifies how many times the preceding element is allowed to repeat.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then any character and then "b".
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then the character "b" at some later point.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] These constructions can be combined to form arbitrarily complex expressions, much like one can construct arithmetical expressions from numbers and the operations +, −, ×, and ÷.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The precise syntax for regular expressions varies among tools and with context; more detail is given in § Syntax.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions describe regular languages in formal language theory.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] They have the same expressive power as regular grammars.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] But the language of regular expressions itself, is context-free language.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions consist of constants, which denote sets of strings, and operator symbols, which denote operations over these sets.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The following definition is standard, and found as such in most textbooks on formal language theory.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] To avoid parentheses, it is assumed that the Kleene star has the highest priority followed by concatenation, then alternation.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] If there is no ambiguity, then parentheses may be omitted.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, `(ab)c` can be written as `abc`, and `a|(b(c*))` can be written as `a|bc*`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Many textbooks use the symbols ∪, +, or ∨ for alternation instead of the vertical bar.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The derivative of a regular expression can be defined using the Brzozowski derivative.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The formal definition of regular expressions is minimal on purpose, and avoids defining `?` and `+`—these can be expressed as follows: `a+`=`aa*`, and `a?`=`(a|ε)`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Sometimes the complement operator is added, to give a *generalized regular expression*; here *Rc* matches all strings over Σ* that do not match *R*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In principle, the complement operator is redundant, because it does not grant any more expressive power.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] However, it can make a regular expression much more concise—eliminating a single complement operator can cause a double exponential blow-up of its length.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions in this sense can express the regular languages, exactly the class of languages accepted by deterministic finite automata.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] There is, however, a significant difference in compactness.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Some classes of regular languages can only be described by deterministic finite automata whose size grows exponentially in the size of the shortest equivalent regular expressions.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The standard example here is the languages *Lk* consisting of all strings over the alphabet {*a*,*b*} whose *k*th-from-last letter equals *a*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] On the one hand, a regular expression describing *L*4 is given by $(a\mid b)^{*}a(a\mid b)(a\mid b)(a\mid b)$ .
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] On the other hand, it is known that every deterministic finite automaton accepting the language *Lk* must have at least 2*k* states.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Luckily, there is a simple mapping from regular expressions to the more general nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs) that does not lead to such a blowup in size; for this reason NFAs are often used as alternative representations of regular languages.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] NFAs are a simple variation of the type-3 grammars of the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In the opposite direction, there are many languages easily described by a DFA that are not easily described by a regular expression.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For instance, determining the validity of a given ISBN requires computing the remainder of an integer modulo 11, and can be easily implemented with an 11-state DFA.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] However, converting it to a regular expression results in a 2.14-megabyte file.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Given a regular expression, Thompson's construction algorithm computes an equivalent nondeterministic finite automaton.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A conversion in the opposite direction is achieved by Kleene's algorithm.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Finally, many real-world "regular expression" engines implement features that cannot be described by the regular expressions in the sense of formal language theory; rather, they implement *regexes*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] As seen in many of the examples above, there is more than one way to construct a regular expression to achieve the same results.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] It is possible to write an algorithm that, for two given regular expressions, decides whether the described languages are equal; the algorithm reduces each expression to a minimal deterministic finite state machine, and determines whether they are isomorphic (equivalent).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] More generally, an equation *E*=*F* between regular-expression terms with variables holds if, and only if, its instantiation with different variables replaced by different symbol constants holds.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Every regular expression can be written solely in terms of the Kleene star and set unions over finite words.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] This is a surprisingly difficult problem.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] As simple as the regular expressions are, there is no method to systematically rewrite them to some normal form.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The lack of axiom in the past led to the star height problem.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In 1991, Dexter Kozen axiomatized regular expressions as a Kleene algebra, using equational and Horn clause axioms.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Already in 1964, Redko had proved that no finite set of purely equational axioms can characterize the algebra of regular languages.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A regex *pattern* matches a target *string*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The pattern is composed of a sequence of *atoms*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] An atom is a single point within the regex pattern which it tries to match to the target string.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The simplest atom is a literal, but grouping parts of the pattern to match an atom will require using `( )` as metacharacters.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A match is made, not when all the atoms of the string are matched, but rather when all the pattern atoms in the regex have matched.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The idea is to make a small pattern of characters stand for a large number of possible strings, rather than compiling a large list of all the literal possibilities.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Depending on the regex processor there are about fourteen metacharacters, characters that may or may not have their literal character meaning, depending on context, or whether they are "escaped", i.e. preceded by an escape sequence, in this case, the backslash `\`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The usual characters that become metacharacters when escaped are `dswDSW` and `N`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] When entering a regex in a programming language, they may be represented as a usual string literal, hence usually quoted; this is common in C, Java, and Python for instance, where the regex `re` is entered as `"re"`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] However, they are often written with slashes as delimiters, as in `/re/` for the regex `re`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A similar convention is used in sed, where search and replace is given by `s/re/replacement/` and patterns can be joined with a comma to specify a range of lines as in `/re1/,/re2/`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] This notation is particularly well known due to its use in Perl, where it forms part of the syntax distinct from normal string literals.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In some cases, such as sed and Perl, alternative delimiters can be used to avoid collision with contents, and to avoid having to escape occurrences of the delimiter character in the contents.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, in sed the command `s,/,X,` will replace a `/` with an `X`, using commas as delimiters.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The IEEE POSIX standard has three sets of compliance: **BRE** (Basic Regular Expressions), **ERE** (Extended Regular Expressions), and **SRE** (Simple Regular Expressions).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] SRE is deprecated, in favor of BRE, as both provide backward compatibility.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The subsection below covering the *character classes* applies to both BRE and ERE.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] ERE adds `?`, `+`, and `|`, and it removes the need to escape the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }`, which are *required* in BRE.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Furthermore, as long as the POSIX standard syntax for regexes is adhered to, there can be, and often is, additional syntax to serve specific (yet POSIX compliant) applications.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Although POSIX.2 leaves some implementation specifics undefined, BRE and ERE provide a "standard" which has since been adopted as the default syntax of many tools, where the choice of BRE or ERE modes is usually a supported option.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, GNU `grep` has the following options: "`grep -E`" for ERE, and "`grep -G`" for BRE (the default), and "`grep -P`" for Perl regexes.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Perl regexes have become a de facto standard, having a rich and powerful set of atomic expressions.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Perl has no "basic" or "extended" levels.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] As in POSIX EREs, `( )` and `{ }` are treated as metacharacters unless escaped; other metacharacters are known to be literal or symbolic based on context alone.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Additional functionality includes lazy matching, backreferences, named capture groups, and recursive patterns.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In the POSIX standard, Basic Regular Syntax (**BRE**) requires that the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }` be designated `\(\)` and `\{\}`, whereas Extended Regular Syntax (**ERE**) does not.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] According to Russ Cox, the POSIX specification requires ambiguous subexpressions to be handled in a way different from Perl's.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The committee replaced Perl's rules with one that is simple to explain, but the new "simple" rules are actually more complex to implement: they were incompatible with pre-existing tooling and made it essentially impossible to define a "lazy match" (see below) extension.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] As a result, very few programs actually implement the POSIX subexpression rules (even when they implement other parts of the POSIX syntax).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The meaning of metacharacters escaped with a backslash is reversed for some characters in the POSIX Extended Regular Expression (**ERE**) syntax.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] With this syntax, a backslash causes the metacharacter to be treated as a literal character.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] POSIX Extended Regular Expressions can often be used with modern Unix utilities by including the command line flag *-E*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The character class is the most basic regex concept after a literal match.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] It makes one small sequence of characters match a larger set of characters.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[A-Z]` could stand for any uppercase letter in the English alphabet, and `\d` could mean any digit.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Character classes apply to both POSIX levels.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] When specifying a range of characters, such as `[a-Z]` (i.e. lowercase *`a`* to uppercase *`Z`*), the computer's locale settings determine the contents by the numeric ordering of the character encoding.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] They could store digits in that sequence, or the ordering could be *abc...zABC...Z*, or *aAbBcC...zZ*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] So the POSIX standard defines a character class, which will be known by the regex processor installed.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] POSIX character classes can only be used within bracket expressions.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[[:upper:]ab]` matches the uppercase letters and lowercase "a" and "b".
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] An additional non-POSIX class understood by some tools is `[:word:]`, which is usually defined as `[:alnum:]` plus underscore.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] This reflects the fact that in many programming languages these are the characters that may be used in identifiers.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Note that what the POSIX regex standards call *character classes* are commonly referred to as *POSIX character classes* in other regex flavors which support them.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] With most other regex flavors, the term *character class* is used to describe what POSIX calls *bracket expressions*.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Because of its expressive power and (relative) ease of reading, many other utilities and programming languages have adopted syntax similar to Perl's—for example, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Python, Ruby, Qt, Microsoft's .NET Framework, and XML Schema.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Some languages and tools such as Boost and PHP support multiple regex flavors.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Perl-derivative regex implementations are not identical and usually implement a subset of features found in Perl 5.0, released in 1994.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Perl sometimes does incorporate features initially found in other languages.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, Perl 5.10 implements syntactic extensions originally developed in PCRE and Python.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In Python and some other implementations (e.g.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Java), the three common quantifiers (`*`, `+`, and `?`) are greedy by default because they match as many characters as possible.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line (because the entire line begins and ends with a double-quote) instead of matching only the first part, `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The aforementioned quantifiers may, however, be made *lazy* or *minimal* or *reluctant*, matching as few characters as possible, by appending a question mark: `".+?"` matches only `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line, the regex `".*+"` does *not match at all*, because `.*+` consumes the entire input, including the final `"`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Thus, possessive quantifiers are most useful with negated character classes, e.g.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] `"[^"]*+"`, which matches `"Ganymede,"` when applied to the same string.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Another common extension serving the same function is atomic grouping, which disables backtracking for a parenthesized group.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, while ^(wi|w)i$ matches both wi and wii, ^(?>wi|w)i$ only matches wii because the engine is forbidden from backtracking and so cannot try setting the group to "w" after matching "wi".
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Possessive quantifiers are easier to implement than greedy and lazy quantifiers, and are typically more efficient at runtime.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] IETF RFC 9485 describes "I-Regexp: An Interoperable Regular Expression Format".
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] It specifies a limited subset of regular-expression idioms designed to be interoperable, i.e. produce the same effect, in a large number of regular-expression libraries.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] I-Regexp is also limited to matching, i.e. providing a true or false match between a regular expression and a given piece of text.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Thus, it lacks advanced features such as capture groups, lookahead, and backreferences.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Many features found in virtually all modern regular expression libraries provide an expressive power that exceeds the regular languages.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, many implementations allow grouping subexpressions with parentheses and recalling the value they match in the same expression (*backreferences*).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] This means that, among other things, a pattern can match strings of repeated words like "papa" or "WikiWiki", called *squares* in formal language theory.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The pattern for these strings is `(.+)\1`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The language of squares is not regular, nor is it context-free, due to the pumping lemma.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] However, pattern matching with an unbounded number of backreferences, as supported by numerous modern tools, is still context sensitive.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The general problem of matching any number of backreferences is NP-complete, and the execution time for known algorithms grows exponentially by the number of backreference groups used.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] However, many tools, libraries, and engines that provide such constructions still use the term *regular expression* for their patterns.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] This has led to a nomenclature where the term regular expression has different meanings in formal language theory and pattern matching.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For this reason, some people have taken to using the term *regex*, *regexp*, or simply *pattern* to describe the latter.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Other features not found in describing regular languages include assertions.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] These include the ubiquitous `^` and `$`, used since at least 1970, as well as some more sophisticated extensions like lookaround that appeared in 1994.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Lookarounds define the surrounding of a match and do not spill into the match itself, a feature only relevant for the use case of string searching.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Some of them can be simulated in a regular language by treating the surroundings as a part of the language as well.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The look-ahead assertions `(?=...)` and `(?!...)` have been attested since at least 1994, starting with Perl 5.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The lookbehind assertions `(?<=...)` and `(?<!...)` are attested since 1997 in a commit by Ilya Zakharevich to Perl 5.005.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] There are at least three different algorithms that decide whether and how a given regex matches a string.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The oldest and fastest relies on a result in formal language theory that allows every nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) to be transformed into a deterministic finite automaton (DFA).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The DFA can be constructed explicitly and then run on the resulting input string one symbol at a time.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Constructing the DFA for a regular expression of size *m* has the time and memory cost of *O*(2*m*), but it can be run on a string of size *n* in time *O*(*n*).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Note that the size of the expression is the size after abbreviations, such as numeric quantifiers, have been expanded.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate the NFA directly, essentially building each DFA state on demand and then discarding it at the next step.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] This keeps the DFA implicit and avoids the exponential construction cost, but running cost rises to *O*(*mn*).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The explicit approach is called the DFA algorithm and the implicit approach the NFA algorithm.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Adding caching to the NFA algorithm is often called the "lazy DFA" algorithm, or just the DFA algorithm without making a distinction.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] These algorithms are fast, but using them for recalling grouped subexpressions, lazy quantification, and similar features is tricky.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Modern implementations include the re1-re2-sregex family based on Cox's code.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] The third algorithm is to match the pattern against the input string by backtracking.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] This algorithm is commonly called NFA, but this terminology can be confusing.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Its running time can be exponential, which simple implementations exhibit when matching against expressions like `(a|aa)*b` that contain both alternation and unbounded quantification and force the algorithm to consider an exponentially increasing number of sub-cases.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] This behavior can cause a security problem called Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Although backtracking implementations only give an exponential guarantee in the worst case, they provide much greater flexibility and expressive power.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] For example, any implementation which allows the use of backreferences, or implements the various extensions introduced by Perl, must include some kind of backtracking.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Some implementations try to provide the best of both algorithms by first running a fast DFA algorithm, and revert to a potentially slower backtracking algorithm only when a backreference is encountered during the match.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep (and the underlying gnulib DFA) uses such a strategy.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Sublinear runtime algorithms have been achieved using Boyer-Moore (BM) based algorithms and related DFA optimization techniques such as the reverse scan.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep, which supports a wide variety of POSIX syntaxes and extensions, uses BM for a first-pass prefiltering, and then uses an implicit DFA.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Wu agrep, which implements approximate matching, combines the prefiltering into the DFA in BDM (backward DAWG matching).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] NR-grep's BNDM extends the BDM technique with Shift-Or bit-level parallelism.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] A few theoretical alternatives to backtracking for backreferences exist, and their "exponents" are tamer in that they are only related to the number of backreferences, a fixed property of some regexp languages such as POSIX.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] One naive method that duplicates a non-backtracking NFA for each backreference note has a complexity of ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})$ ⁠ time and ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})$ ⁠ space for a haystack of length n and k backreferences in the RegExp.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Theoretical work based on memory automata gives a tighter bound based on "active" variable nodes used, and a polynomial possibility for some backreferenced regexps.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In theoretical terms, any token set can be matched by regular expressions as long as it is pre-defined.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In terms of historical implementations, regexes were originally written to use ASCII characters as their token set though regex libraries have supported numerous other character sets.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Many modern regex engines offer at least some support for Unicode.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] In most respects it makes no difference what the character set is, but some issues do arise when extending regexes to support Unicode.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p01] Most general-purpose programming languages support regex capabilities, either natively or via libraries.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Regexes are useful in a wide variety of text processing tasks, and more generally string processing, where the data need not be textual.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Common applications include data validation, data scraping (especially web scraping), data wrangling, simple parsing, the production of syntax highlighting systems, and many other tasks.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Some high-end desktop publishing software has the ability to use regexes to automatically apply text styling, saving the person doing the layout from laboriously doing this by hand for anything that can be matched by a regex.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] For example, by defining a character style that makes text into small caps and then using the regex `[A-Z]{4,}` to apply that style, any word of four or more consecutive capital letters will be automatically rendered as small caps instead.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] While regexes would be useful on Internet search engines, processing them across the entire database could consume excessive computer resources depending on the complexity and design of the regex.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Although in many cases system administrators can run regex-based queries internally, most search engines do not offer regex support to the public.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Notable exceptions include Google Code Search and Exalead.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] However, Google Code Search was shut down in January 2012.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] The specific syntax rules vary depending on the specific implementation, programming language, or library in use.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Additionally, the functionality of regex implementations can vary between versions.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Because regexes can be difficult to both explain and understand without examples, interactive websites for testing regexes are a useful resource for learning regexes by experimentation.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] This section provides a basic description of some of the properties of regexes by way of illustration.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] The following conventions are used in the examples.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Standard POSIX regular expressions are different.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Unless otherwise indicated, the following examples conform to the Perl programming language, release 5.8.8, January 31, 2006.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] This means that other implementations may lack support for some parts of the syntax shown here (e.g. basic vs. extended regex, `\( \)` vs.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] The syntax and conventions used in these examples coincide with that of other programming environments as well.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Regular expressions can often be created ("induced" or "learned") based on a set of example strings.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] This is known as the induction of regular languages and is part of the general problem of grammar induction in computational learning theory.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Formally, given examples of strings in a regular language, and perhaps also given examples of strings *not* in that regular language, it is possible to induce a grammar for the language, i.e., a regular expression that generates that language.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] Not all regular languages can be induced in this way (see language identification in the limit), but many can.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/regular-expression-p02] For example, the set of examples {1, 10, 100}, and negative set (of counterexamples) {11, 1001, 101, 0} can be used to induce the regular expression 1⋅0* (1 followed by zero or more 0s).
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The goal with this cheat Sheet is to present a concise virtual patching framework that organizations can follow to maximize the timely implementation of mitigation protections.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The virtual patch works when the security enforcement layer analyzes transactions and intercepts attacks in transit, so malicious traffic never reaches the web application.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The resulting impact of virtual patching is that, while the actual source code of the application itself has not been modified, the exploitation attempt does not succeed.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] From a purely technical perspective, the number one remediation strategy would be for an organization to correct the identified vulnerability within the source code of the web application.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] This concept is universally agreed upon by both web application security experts and system owners.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The important point is this - **Code level fixes and Virtual Patching are NOT mutually exclusive**.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] They are processes that are executed by different team (OWASP Builders/Devs vs.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] OWASP Defenders/OpSec) and can be run in tandem.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] For example purposes, we will show virtual patching examples using the open source ModSecurity WAF tool.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Virtual Patching, like most other security processes, is not something that should be approached haphazardly.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Instead, a consistent, repeatable process should be followed that will provide the best chances of success.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] WordPress Shopping Cart Plugin for WordPress contains a flaw that may allow an attacker to carry out an SQL injection attack.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The issue is due to the `/wp-content/plugins/levelfourstorefront/scripts/administration/exportsubscribers.php` script not properly sanitizing user-supplied input to the `reqID` parameter.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] This may allow an attacker to inject or manipulate SQL queries in the back-end database, allowing for the manipulation or disclosure of arbitrary data.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The importance of properly utilizing the preparation phase with regards to virtual patching cannot be overstated.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] You need to do a number of things to setup the virtual patching processes and framework **prior** to actually having to deal with an identified vulnerability, or worse yet, react to a live web application intrusion.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The point is that during a live compromise is not the ideal time to be proposing installation of a web application firewall and the concept of a virtual patch.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Tension is high during real incidents and time is of the essence, so lay the foundation of virtual patching when the waters are calm and get everything in place and ready to go when an incident does occur.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The Identification Phase occurs when an organization becomes aware of a vulnerability within their web application.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] There are generally two different methods of identifying vulnerabilities: `Proactive` and `Reactive`.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Due to the fact that custom coded web applications are unique, these proactive identification tasks are extremely important as you are not able to rely upon third-party vulnerability notifications.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] **Utilize Bug Tracking/Ticketing System** - Enter the vulnerability information into a bug tracking system for tracking purposes and metrics.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Recommend you use ticketing systems you already use such as Jira or you may use a specialized tool such as ThreadFix.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] **Verify the name of the vulnerability** - This means that you need to have the proper public vulnerability identifier (such as CVE name/number) specified by the vulnerability announcement, vulnerability scan, etc.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] If the vulnerability is identified proactively rather than through public announcements, then you should assign your own unique identifier to each vulnerability.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] **Designate the impact level** - It is always important to understand the level of criticality involved with a web vulnerability.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Information leakages may not be treated in the same manner as an SQL Injection issue.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] **Specify which versions of software are impacted** - You need to identify what versions of software are listed so that you can determine if the version(s) you have installed are affected.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] **List what configuration is required to trigger the problem** - Some vulnerabilities may only manifest themselves under certain configuration settings.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] **List Proof of Concept (PoC) exploit code or payloads used during attacks/testing** - Many vulnerability announcements have accompanying exploit code that shows how to demonstrate the vulnerability.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] If this data is available, make sure to download it for analysis.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] This will be useful later on when both developing and testing the virtual patch.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] **No false negatives** - Do not ever miss attacks, even when the attacker intentionally tries to evade detection.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Care should be taken to attempt to minimize either of these two rules.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] It may not be possible to adhere 100% to each of these goals but remember that virtual patching is about **Risk Reduction**.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] It should be understood by business owners that while you are gaining the advantage of shortening the Time-to-Fix metric, you may not be implementing a complete fix for the flaw.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Positive security model (allowlist) is a comprehensive security mechanism that provides an independent input validation envelope to an application.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] The model specifies the characteristics of valid input (character set, length, etc…) and denies anything that does not conform.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] By defining rules for every parameter in every page in the application the application is protected by an additional security envelop independent from its code.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] In order to create an allow-list virtual patch, you must be able to verify what the normal, expected input values are.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] If you have implemented proper audit logging as part of the Preparation Phase, then you should be able to review audit logs to identify the format of expected input types.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] This virtual patch will inspect the `reqID` parameter value on the specified page and prevent any characters other than integers as input.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] A negative security model (denylist) is based on a set of rules that detect specific known attacks rather than allow only valid traffic.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Looking at the payload, we can see that the attacker is inserting a single quote character and then adding additional SQL query logic to the end.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] A virtual patch may employ either a positive or negative security model.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Which one you decide to use depends on the situation and a few different considerations.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] For example, negative security rules can usually be implemented more quickly, however the possible evasions are more likely.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Positive security rules, only the other hand, provides better protection however it is often a manual process and thus is not scalable and difficult to maintain for large/dynamic sites.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] While manual positive security rules for an entire site may not be feasible, a positive security model can be selectively employed when a vulnerability alert identifies a specific location with a problem.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] You want to resist the urge to take the easy road and quickly create an **exploit-specific virtual patch**.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] It would not be wise to implement a virtual patch that simply blocks that exact payload.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] While it may provide some immediate protection, its long term value is significantly decreased.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] Manual patch creation may become unfeasible as the number of vulnerabilities grow and automated means may become necessary.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] If the vulnerabilities were identified using automated tools and an XML report is available, it is possible to leverage automated processes to auto-convert this vulnerability data into virtual patches for protection systems.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/virtual-patching-cheat-sheet] In order to accurately test out the newly created virtual patches, it may be necessary to use an application other than a web browser.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] A **Web application firewall** (**WAF**) is a specific form of application firewall that filters, monitors, and blocks HTTP traffic to and from a web service.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] By inspecting HTTP traffic, it can prevent attacks exploiting a Web application's known vulnerabilities, such as SQL injection, cross-site scripting (XSS), file inclusion, and improper system configuration.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] Financial institutions often utilize WAFs to help in the mitigation of Web application zero-day vulnerabilities, as well as hard-to-patch bugs or weaknesses through custom attack signature strings.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] Dedicated Web application firewalls entered the market in the late 1990s during a time when web server attacks were becoming more prevalent.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] Early WAF products, from Kavado and Gilian technologies, tried to solve the increasing amount of attacks on Web applications in the late 1990s.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] In 2002, the open-source project ModSecurity was formed in order to make WAF technology more accessible.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] They finalized a core rule set for protecting Web applications, based on OASIS Web Application Security Technical Committee’s (WAS TC) vulnerability work.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] In 2003, they expanded and standardized rules through the Open Web Application Security Project’s (OWASP) Top 10 List, an annual ranking for Web security vulnerabilities.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] This list would become the industry standard for Web application security compliance.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] Since then, the market has continued to grow and evolve, especially focusing on credit card fraud prevention.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] With the development of the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS), a standardization of control over cardholder data, security has become more regulated in this sector.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] A Web application firewall is a special type of application firewall that applies specifically to Web applications.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] It is deployed in front of Web applications and analyzes bi-directional web-based (HTTP) traffic – detecting and blocking anything malicious.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] The OWASP provides a broad technical definition for a WAF as “a security solution on the Web application level which – from a technical point of view – does not depend on the application itself”.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] According to the PCI DSS Information Supplement for requirement 6.6, a WAF is defined as “a security policy enforcement point positioned between a Web application and the client endpoint.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] This functionality can be implemented in software or hardware, running in an appliance device, or in a typical server running a common operating system.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] It may be a stand-alone device or integrated into other network components.” In other words, a WAF can be a virtual or physical appliance that prevents vulnerabilities in Web applications from being exploited by outside threats.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] These vulnerabilities may be because the application itself is a legacy type or was insufficiently coded by design.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] The WAF addresses these code shortcomings by special configurations of rule-sets, also known as policies.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] Previously unknown vulnerabilities can be discovered through penetration testing or via a vulnerability scanner.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] A Web application vulnerability scanner, also known as a web application security scanner, is defined in the SAMATE NIST 500-269 as “an automated program that examines Web applications for potential security vulnerabilities.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] In addition to searching for Web application-specific vulnerabilities, the tools also look for software coding errors.” Resolving vulnerabilities is commonly referred to as remediation.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] Corrections to the code can be made in the application, but typically a more prompt response is necessary.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] In these situations, the application of a custom policy for a unique Web application vulnerability to provide a temporary but immediate fix (known as a virtual patch) may be necessary.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] WAFs are not an ultimate security solution, rather they are meant to be used in conjunction with other network perimeter security solutions such as network firewalls and intrusion prevention systems to provide a holistic defense strategy.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] WAFs typically follow a positive security model, a negative security, or a combination of both as mentioned by the SANS Institute.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] WAFs use a combination of rule-based logic, parsing, and signatures to detect and prevent attacks such as cross-site scripting and SQL injection.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] In general, features like browser emulation, obfuscation and virtualization, and IP obfuscation are used to attempt to bypass WAFs.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] The OWASP produces a list of the top ten Web application security flaws.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] All commercial WAF offerings cover these ten flaws at a minimum.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] There are non-commercial options as well.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] As mentioned earlier, the well-known open-source WAF engine called ModSecurity is one of these options.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] A WAF engine alone is insufficient to provide adequate protection, therefore OWASP along with Trustwave's Spiderlabs help organize and maintain a Core-Rule Set via GitHub to use with the ModSecurity WAF engine.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] Although the names for operating mode may differ, WAFs are basically deployed inline in three different ways.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] According to NSS Labs, deployment options are transparent bridge, transparent reverse proxy, and reverse proxy.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] "Transparent" refers to the fact that the HTTP traffic is sent straight to the Web application, therefore the WAF is transparent between the client and server.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] This is in contrast to reverse proxy, where the WAF acts as a proxy, and the client’s traffic is sent directly to the WAF.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] The WAF then separately sends filtered traffic to Web applications.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] This can provide additional benefits such as IP masking but may introduce disadvantages such as performance latencies.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] JA3, developed by Salesforce in 2017, is a technique for generating a unique fingerprint for SSL/TLS traffic based on specific fields in the handshake, such as the version, cipher suites, and extensions used by the client.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] This fingerprint enables the identification and tracking of clients based on the characteristics of their encrypted traffic.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] In the context of distributed denial of service (DDoS) protection, JA3 fingerprints are used to detect and differentiate malicious traffic, often associated with attack bots, from legitimate traffic, allowing for more precise filtering of potential threats.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] In September 2023, AWS WAF announced built-in support for JA3, enabling customers to inspect the JA3 fingerprints of incoming requests.
[src:waf-rule-tuning/web-application-firewall] JA3 was deprecated in May 2025 in favor of JA4.
